<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIPS TO CULTIVATE A LIVELY BACK YARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHARON COHOON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Here are some sources of information on converting your garden into a 
back-yard wildlife habitat: 
</P>
<P>
 * Send for the National Wildlife Federation's packet on the Backyard Wildlife 
Habitat program. The packet contains an application form, a booklet on planning 
and planting a habitat, and the paperback "The Backyard Naturalist," describing 
the experiences of the manager of the program in creating a habitat. Send a 
check for $5.25 (includes postage and handling) to the National Wildlife 
Federation, 1400 16th St., N.W., Washington, D.C., 20036-2266, or call its 
toll-free number, (800) 432-6564, to order. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Your Backyard Wildlife Garden," by Marcus Schneck (Rodale Press, 1992, 
$25), is an excellent introduction to the subject. It explains how to look at 
your yard from the viewpoint of an animal, contains many useful charts (such as 
lists of plants to attract hummingbirds and specific butterflies and birds), 
lots of photos for inspiration, fun ideas (such as creating a toad house) and a 
great pictorial glossary in the back with all the common wild creatures likely 
to be attracted to a typical back yard. Even the kids will enjoy referring to 
the glossary. 
</P>
<P>
 * Another good basic book is "Attracting Backyard Wildlife," by Bill Merilees 
(Voyageur Press, 1989, $10.95), available in most libraries. 
</P>
<P>
 * Back-yard habitats from the standpoint of design are featured in 
"Landscaping With Nature," by Jeff Cox (Rodale Press, 1991, $27). The author 
explains in detail how to simulate nature in our own back yards and proves that 
doing so is not only more compatible with wildlife but also can be more 
aesthetically pleasing. 
</P>
<P>
 * "The Natural Habitat Garden," by Ken Druse (Clarkson Potter, $40) due out in 
March. This third book by writer-photographer Druse on the naturalistic garden 
will emphasize the benefits of native plant gardening and include instructions 
for firescaping. 
</P>
<P>
 * Sea & Sage, the local chapter of the Audubon Society, can help you learn 
what kinds of birds you can expect to attract. Call (714) 261-7963 for 
information. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Butterflies of Greater Los Angeles" is an illustrated guide to the 106 
species in the area. Order from Theodore Payne Foundation, (818) 768-1802. 
About $8. 
</P>
<P>
 * Fullerton Arboretum propagates many native plant species for its weekend 
plant sales. Call (714) 773-3579 for more information. Tree of Life Nursery in 
San Clemente is another good local source of native plants. (714) 728-0685. 
</P>
<P>
 * For inspiration, visit some gardens that are already good habitats. Hortense 
Miller's in Laguna Beach is a good one. Call the city of Laguna Beach at (714) 
494-0716 to make reservations for a tour. For ideas on how to incorporate 
native plants into the landscaping, visit the Home Demonstration Garden at the 
Santa Barbara Botanic Garden, (805) 682-0988; the Rancho Santa Ana Botanical 
Garden, (909) 625-8767 in Claremont, or the Theodore Payne Foundation, (818) 
768-1802 in Sun Valley. SHARON COHOON 
</P>
</TEXT>
