<DATE>
<P>
February 12, 1994, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 3; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
96 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEY, MAYBE THIS GUY SHOULD BE COMMISSIONER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I had a dream that Paul Tagliabue took over baseball and now home runs to 
center field are worth two runs and runners on second base have microphones 
connected to their helmets to tell the batter the catcher's signs. 
</P>
<P>
 Pro football is the only sport in which every season fans (and players) are 
forced to learn three or four new rules just to follow along.  
</P>
<P>
 Just leave it alone, NFL. Field goals are worth three points, kickoffs are 
from the 35-yard line and the quarterback can fend for himself against loud 
crowds and oncoming rushers. 
</P>
<P>
 MARK J. KIELY 
</P>
<P>
 Mission Viejo 
</P>
</TEXT>
