<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; LIBRARY GIFT STORE MOVES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Thousand Oaks Library Foundation, a nonprofit agency that raises funds to 
support library programs, has opened a makeshift gift store in The Oaks mall. 
</P>
<P>
 Last month's earthquake seriously damaged the library on Janss Road, forcing 
the foundation store to close.But little of the store's merchandise was 
destroyed, and foundation directors decided to move the inventory to The Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
 The new store, open during regular mall hours, is on the upper level just west 
of The Oaks' main entrance. Foundation board member Frances Prince said she 
expects the mall store to remain open for four to six weeks, until library 
renovations are complete. 
</P>
<P>
 The new location is already bringing some benefits. A young woman striding by 
during her mall-walking class one morning offered to volunteer in the store, 
Prince said, adding: "We signed her up on the spot." 
</P>
<P>
 To give residents a peek at the library during the renovations, the Friends of 
the Library group will hold a Hard Hat Art Day from 1 to 3 p.m. March 5. 
</P>
<P>
 For a $1 donation, visitors will be able to scribble on the library's floor 
with crayons or chalk, to leave their mark before the new carpeting is 
installed. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't expect it to make a lot of money," organizer Kathy Lewis said. "But 
kids and adults will enjoy it, and it will keep the library in their minds." 
STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</TEXT>
