<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEAMSTERS FILE 2ND COMPLAINT AGAINST FIRM IN TRANSIT STRIKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHARON MOESER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The union representing employees striking against the operator of the Antelope 
Valley's public transit system has again accused the bus company of unfair 
labor practices. 
</P>
<P>
 The National Labor Relations Board late last year dismissed the first charge. 
Ralph Phillips, an Encino attorney representing the Teamsters, said a request 
for a review of that decision has been filed with the labor board's office of 
appeals in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're keeping up the battle," Phillips said. "Hopefully, this one will 
stick." 
</P>
<P>
 Some 85 bus drivers, mechanics and other employees who had voted to join the 
Teamsters went on strike in late October. Although the work stoppage 
temporarily disrupted service, replacement workers were hired within weeks. The 
workers continue to picket outside the DAVE Transportation offices in 
Lancaster. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest complaint, filed Jan. 28, accuses DAVE Transportation of 
"misrepresenting its financial conditions to (the union) during contract 
negotiations." 
</P>
<P>
 Phillips said that during negotiations, the company claimed that it was unable 
to pay the wages requested by the union because its revenues from operating the 
public transportation system for the Antelope Valley Transit Authority were 
insufficient. 
</P>
<P>
 A review of the company's financial records by the union, according to 
Phillips, found the claim to be false. 
</P>
<P>
 John Helm, a regional manager with DAVE Transportation, said he is confident 
that the latest complaint will also be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't believe there's any basis to this unfair labor practice (charge) 
just as the National Labor Relations Board found no basis for their previous 
charge," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We stated during the negotiations that we were unwilling to meet their 
requests because of our financial performance, and we offered to allow their 
auditors to look at our books. And that took place." 
</P>
<P>
 Other than receiving a notice from the NLRB that a complaint had been filed, 
Helm said he has heard nothing from the union. 
</P>
<P>
 The first complaint involved allegations of failing to bargain in good faith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
